hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the function $f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, known as Thomae's function, which is defined as follows:
$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
\frac{1}{q}  \text{if } x = \frac{p}{q} \text{ is a rational number in lowest terms with } q \in \mathbb{Z}, q  0 \\
0  \text{if } x \text{ is an irrational number}
\end{cases}
$$
By this definition, for example, $f(3/4) = 1/4$, $f(5) = f(5/1) = 1$, and $f(\sqrt{2}) = 0$. We also adopt the standard convention that $f(0) = f(0/1) = 1$.

Let $c$ be an arbitrary non-zero rational number. Your task is to determine the value of the left-hand limit and the right-hand limit of $f(x)$ as $x$ approaches $c$.

Let $L^{-} = \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x)$ and $L^{+} = \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x)$. Determine the values of $L^{-}$ and $L^{+}$. Report the two values in the order $L^{-}$, then $L^{+}$.
